<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
HAITI; 
</P>
<P>
ELECTION DATE TO BE FIXED NEXT WEEK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Haiti will hold its first free elections in 186 years by October and the voting 
will be supervised by international observers, the electoral council announced. 
</P>
<P>
Council President Jean-Robert Sabalat said the exact date will be announced 
next week. Balloting will be held for local offices, seats in Parliament and 
for the presidency, he added. Seventeen candidates have already announced for 
the presidency. Haiti, the first republic of former slaves, gained independence 
from France in 1804 and has since been governed mostly by repressive military 
rulers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
