<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: YORBA LINDA; 
</P>
<P>
NO GAS OR FAST FOOD AT SITE OF NEW CENTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LINDA M. HICKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council has agreed to allow a shopping center planned for the east end 
of the city to expand by 3.6 acres but refused to allow a gas station and 
fast-food restaurant there. 
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the center, which is expected to include a Ralphs market and 
Thrifty Drug Store, was allowed in a 3-1 vote. Council member Henry W. Wedaa 
was not present. 
</P>
<P>
The council voted unanimously against plans for a gas station and a fast-food 
restaurant which, they argued, would bring commuter traffic into the city from 
the Riverside Freeway. 
</P>
<P>
"I will not vote for any gas station that invites commuters to stop and buy 
gas," said Councilman Irwin Fried. 
</P>
<P>
John O'Mara, a representative of the Costa Mesa-based Diversified Shopping 
Center Inc., said that without the gas station and Carl's Jr. restaurant, 
developers would "have to make some major changes to make this project fiscally 
feasible." 
</P>
<P>
About 30 residents appeared at the meeting Tuesday, and many agreed with Fried 
and the other council members. 
</P>
<P>
"These components will turn our neighborhood into a commuter pit stop," said 
resident Leslie Boies. 
</P>
<P>
But those who spoke in favor of the expansion said a large, well-planned 
shopping center is needed at the corner of La Palma Avenue and Via Lomas de 
Yorba East, because the nearest grocery store is more than four miles away. 
</P>
<P>
Resident Ken Ryan said the city has a responsibility to make such amenities 
available to those who live in the area. "If they weren't going to provide 
these services, they shouldn't have allowed so many (housing) units in the east 
end of town," he said. 
</P>
<P>
O'Mara said the inclusion of the parcel next to the site is necessary because 
it would give the center access to a side street, increasing convenience for 
shoppers. 
</P>
<P>
Councilman Mark Schwing cast the only vote against any expansion, stating that 
an environmental impact report of the plans for the larger site should be 
submitted to the council before any decision is made. LINDA M. HICKMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
