<TEXT>
<P>
McDonald's Corp. said today it will post complete nutritional information -- 
including fat and sodium levels -- on all of its products at its restaurants by 
the end of July. 
</P>
<P>
"The more (customers) know about McDonald's food, . . . the easier it will be 
for them to see how McDonald's fits into their balanced diet," said Terri 
Capatosto, spokeswoman for the fast-food giant. 
</P>
<P>
McDonald's drew fire from anti-cholesterol crusader Phil Sokolof this spring 
when the Omaha industrialist took out full-page ads in newspapers across the 
country pleading with McDonald's to cut the fat in its hamburgers. 
</P>
<P>
Sokolof's ad, under the headline "The Poisoning of America," was attacked by 
McDonald's as misleading and malicious. 
</P>
