<HEADLINE>
<P>
WESTMINSTER BASEBALL COACH OSTROWSKI QUITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM HAMILTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ken Ostrowski, who led Westminster High School's baseball team to the Southern 
Section playoffs in three of the past four seasons, has resigned his position 
because of differences with the school's administration. 
</P>
<P>
Ostrowski called a team meeting and announced his decision Thursday afternoon 
but declined to comment publicly. 
</P>
<P>
Westminster slumped to a 6-16 record and won only one game in the Sunset League 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
Westminster averaged 17 victories per season from 1986 to 1988 and produced 
some of the top players in the county, including first baseman Ryan Klesko and 
pitcher Brett Grebe, who are playing in the Atlanta Braves' minor league 
system. TOM HAMILTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
RESIGNATIONS; COACHES; BASEBALL; WESTMINSTER HIGH SCHOOL; OSTROWSKI, KEN 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
